<line id="74"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">        </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;item</span> <span class="attribute">handle=</span><span class="value">"theology"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Theology</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/item&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="75"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">      </span><span class="tag close">&lt;/category&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="76"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">    </span><span class="tag close">&lt;/entry&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="77"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">  </span><span class="tag close">&lt;/article&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="78"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">  </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;featured-articles</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="79"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">    </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;section</span> <span class="attribute">id=</span><span class="value">"7"</span> <span class="attribute">handle=</span><span class="value">"articles"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Articles</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/section&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="80"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">    </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;entry</span> <span class="attribute">id=</span><span class="value">"115"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="81"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">      </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;title</span> <span class="attribute">mode=</span><span class="value">"formatted"</span> <span class="attribute">handle=</span><span class="value">"how-to-talk-about-god"</span> <span class="attribute">word-count=</span><span class="value">"5"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">How to Talk about God</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/title&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="82"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">      </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;body</span> <span class="attribute">mode=</span><span class="value">"formatted"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">For a long time now I have been uncomfortable with the language that traditional theology uses and offers to all of us to talk about God. Primarily this is the language of "God is like ..." or "God is not like ..." This comes from a belief that we cannot describe what God is really like. It is true that we cannot know everything about God and that there will always be something to learn and discover about Him. But there has to come a time when we have "seen" God, when we have "known" Him and a real authentic relationship can develop between Him and us. A time when we have become His children.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="83"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="84"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">To do justice to traditional theology we need to acknowledge that there are times when the biblical authors use the language of "God is like". In fact, Jesus himself makes use extensively of this language especially in the parables to instruct the people who were less familiar with God and His ways in the world. For instance, the Parable of the Prodigal Son tells the story of </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;em</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">a father</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="text"> (Luke 15). However, when Jesus is with the disciples at the end of His ministry when they were more familiar with His teaching, Jesus stops communicating in parables. He speaks plainly and talks about </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;em</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">the Father</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="text"> (John 14). Before, He used the language of instruction. Now, He uses the language of intimacy. Before, He used the language of what things could be showing the possibility of forgiveness and restoration. Now, he uses the language of what things really are celebrating the reality of the relationship between God and human beings.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="85"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="86"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">This is the language of metaphor because metaphors temporarily lend the properties of well known objects, beings, phenomena to those that are less known or harder to describe. For instance, the Romanian poet Mihai Eminescu tells the story of a king's daughter that the Morning Star falls in love with. The poet came from the Greek Orthodox tradition where the Virgin Mary is highly regarded by believers. In order to emphasise the unique beauty of the princess and the consideration she enjoyed from her parents the poet likened her position to that of the Virgin among the saints or of the Moon among the stars. So for the sake of understanding the uniqueness of the king's daughter Eminescu </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;em</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">temporarily</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="text"> lends her </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;em</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">some</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="text"> of the attributes of the Virgin and of the Moon. I've emphasised "temporarily" and "some" because the poet doesn't claim for the girl to be just as the Virgin Mary. This would have been a sacrilege. But temporarily for the sake of us understanding what made the Morning Star fall in love with this girl the poet employs a metaphor. Then the metaphor doesn't create a relationship of equivalence between the girl and the Virgin but between her position in the kingdom and the position of the Virgin among the saints.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="87"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="88"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">We imagine the spiritual world as something fuzzy, formless, unsubstantial, just at the level of the mind, something that cannot be seen, distinguished, yet present. However, in the Hebrew tradition, the spiritual is as real, fully formed, developed as it can ever be. In fact, it is more formed, more real, than this world.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="89"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text"></span><span class="tag close">&lt;/body&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="90"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">      </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;date</span> <span class="attribute">time=</span><span class="value">"12:36"</span> <span class="attribute">weekday=</span><span class="value">"3"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">2012-07-18</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/date&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="91"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">    </span><span class="tag close">&lt;/entry&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="92"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">    </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;entry</span> <span class="attribute">id=</span><span class="value">"87"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="93"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">      </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;title</span> <span class="attribute">mode=</span><span class="value">"formatted"</span> <span class="attribute">handle=</span><span class="value">"for-not-even-his-brothers-believed-in-him"</span> <span class="attribute">word-count=</span><span class="value">"8"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">For not even </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;strong</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">His brothers</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/strong&gt;</span><span class="text"> believed in Him</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/title&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
<line id="94"><marker></marker><content><span class="context-markup xml"><span class="text">      </span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;body</span> <span class="attribute">mode=</span><span class="value">"formatted"</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="tag open"><span class="begin">&lt;p</span><span class="end">&gt;</span></span><span class="text">Life wasn't easy for Jesus: He travelled around as a teacher and healer.</span><span class="tag close">&lt;/p&gt;</span><span class="text"></span></span></content></line>
